{# MENU: board — the menu as a letter board.

   Two typographic columns on a ruled ground, grouped under category rules,
   reusing the label / dotted-leader / value mechanics of .ledger-row at menu
   scale. Item names in Fraunces, prices in Inter with tabular figures.

   Serves any client with a long real menu (20+ items that change) — a bistro,
   wine bar, bakery — where the card grid degenerates into a wall of identical
   boxes. The correct affordance for a long list is a typographic list with no
   imagery, which is also why this is not predictable from "restaurant
   website": the reflex there is a card grid with a photo per dish.

   `price` on a menu item is OPTIONAL. Without it the leader and the price are
   dropped and the row is just name + note, so an existing config with no
   prices switches to this variant without breaking.

   MOTION NOTE: the container carries `.menu-grid`, which is already in the
   staggerReveal() selector list in animations.js, and this variant does not
   wrap itself in `.reveal` — so unlike menu/grid, the items here can actually
   deal out instead of being skipped by the closest('.reveal') guard. #}
{% set groups = site.menu_items | groupBy("category") %}
<div class="board">
  {% for category, items in groups %}
  <div class="board-group">
    {% if category %}<div class="board-cat">{{ category }}</div>{% endif %}
    <div class="menu-grid menu-grid--board">
      {% for item in items %}
      <div class="board-item">
        <div class="board-line">
          <span class="bname">{{ item.title }}</span>
          {% if item.price %}<span class="bdots"></span><span class="bprice">{{ item.price }}</span>{% endif %}
        </div>
        {% if item.short %}<p class="bnote">{{ item.short }}</p>{% endif %}
        {% if item.badge %}<span class="tier-chip">{{ item.badge }}</span>{% endif %}
      </div>
      {% endfor %}
    </div>
  </div>
  {% endfor %}
</div>
